<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/46387D84-F71E-4B7D-8C7D-9C288F113510"><gtr:id>46387D84-F71E-4B7D-8C7D-9C288F113510</gtr:id><gtr:name>Imperial College London</gtr:name><gtr:department>Biological Sciences</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>South Kensington Campus</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Exhibition Road</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>SW7 2AZ</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/46387D84-F71E-4B7D-8C7D-9C288F113510"><gtr:id>46387D84-F71E-4B7D-8C7D-9C288F113510</gtr:id><gtr:name>Imperial College London</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>South Kensington Campus</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Exhibition Road</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>SW7 2AZ</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/E7089A0C-3AF5-4362-AC59-39055DA6FD73"><gtr:id>E7089A0C-3AF5-4362-AC59-39055DA6FD73</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Gad</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Frankel</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/projects?ref=G0401551"><gtr:id>45401DDB-BBAD-419F-8C27-54663613B34A</gtr:id><gtr:title>Enterohaemorrhagic E. coli infection: identification of the host cell intimin receptor (Hir)</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>G0401551</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Escherichia coli (or E. coli) is the name of a normally harmless bacterium that lives in the human gut. However, a few strains of E. coli have acquired the ability to cause disease. Enteropathogenic E. coli (EPEC for short) and enterohaemorrhagic E. coli (EHEC for short and also known as E. coli O157) are two such closely related strains of E. coli that cause diarrhoeal diseases in man and sometimes cause death. EPEC is a cause of infant disease particularly in third world countries whereas EHEC is a food-borne pathogen common in developed countries; a few recent fatal E. coli O157 outbreaks in the U.K. have highlighted the importance of this recently emerged pathogen. In order to cause disease these bacteria, once consumed, must stick to the lining of the gut and grow to large numbers, a process known as colonisation. EPEC and EHEC express a surface protein known as intimin, which plays a central role in colonisation of the gut epithelium. Previous reports have shown that the EPEC/EHEC bacterium injects a receptor known as Tir (translocated intimin receptor) into the host cell that intimin binds to. However, a large body of evidence point to existence of an intimin receptor which is of cellular origin which we tentatively call Hir (host intimin receptor). Although Hir seems to play a major role in colonisation, its identity is still unknown. The aim of this investigation is to identify and characterise candidate Hir. This will aid in understanding the molecular basis of EHEC and EPEC infection and in the development of novel intervention compounds.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>In the UK and overseas, there is an increasing occurrence of foodborne illnesses associated with enterohaemorrhagic Escherichia coli (EHEC). Infections with EHEC cause a wide spectrum of disease in humans ranging from mild diarrhoea to haemorrhagic colitis and haemolytic uraemic syndrome (HUS). EHEC and the closely related enteropathogenic E. coli (EPEC), which are a major cause of infantile diarrhoea, share many virulence determinants. Intimin, a major EHEC/EPEC virulence factor, is an outer membrane adhesion molecule that mediates bacterial attachment to epithelial cells. EPEC O127:H6 express a specific intimin type known as intimin alpha while EHEC O157:H7 expresses intimin gamma. Intimin binds the well-characterised bacterial derived translocated receptor Tir. However, a growing body of evidence now points to the existence of a second, mucosal-encoded intimin receptor, including the fact that intimin alpha and intimin gamma a) bind uninfected cells, b) mediate close Tir-independent attachment to human intestial explants and c) contribute to tissue specificity within the gut epithelium. We recently demonstrated similar intimin-mediated attachemnt and tissue specificity in intestinal porcine explants. The lack of knowledge of the mucosal host cell-encoded intimin receptor (Hir) represents a significant gap in our understanding of EPEC and EHEC. The aim of this project is to identify novel Hir candidates. We will use porcine and human intestinal explants and primary enterocytes together with molecular, biochemical and cellular approaches to characterise intimin:Hir protein interactions, to determine the involvement of Hir in cell attachment and to establish if Hir/s or anti Hir antibodies have the ability to block EPEC/EHEC cell attachment.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-01-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2005-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>220000</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gt